{"id": "aby-becibi", "type": "outcome", "title": "First-loop integration is specified end-to-end, not hand-waved", "brief": {"why": "We're proceeding on vibes. The components exist (daemon, router, prompts, spawn) but the runtime contracts are undefined: how does the aboyeur invoke spawnAgent? What MCP config do one-shots get? How does served mise connect to the daemon poll? Every session re-derives these answers. Without a spec, the next builder will make incompatible assumptions.", "what": "1. Update architecture-decisions.md with post-March-6 changes (mise-as-daemon-eyes, mesh, two-channel insight) 2. Write runtime integration spec: process diagram showing exact data flow from trigger arrival through to draft-in-Gmail 3. Specify MCP config for each session tier (aboyeur, one-shot, PM, worker) 4. Specify how aboyeur calls spawnAgent (MCP tool? direct import? daemon callback?) 5. Specify served mise endpoint contract for daemon polling", "done": "A new Claude can read the spec and build aby-sanimu without asking 'but how does X connect to Y?' Every arrow in the diagram names the actual mechanism (function call, HTTP endpoint, file deposit, CLI invocation)."}, "status": "open", "order": 16, "created_at": "2026-03-15T17:30:25Z", "created_by": "spm1001"}
{"id": "aby-bunuza", "type": "action", "title": "Per-context FIFO queue with concurrency limits", "brief": {"why": "Need sequential processing within a context (e.g. one email thread) but parallel processing across contexts. NanoClaw's GroupQueue pattern: per-group FIFO, global max of 3 concurrent agents, exponential backoff on failure.", "what": "1. Queue class: enqueue(contextId, triggerFn), drain(), shutdown() 2. Per-context ordering (FIFO within a context group) 3. Global concurrency limit (configurable, default 3) 4. Exponential backoff on spawn failure (5s base, max 5 retries) 5. Lane policy per context: followup (default), steer (interrupt), or collect (batch)", "done": "Three triggers for different contexts process in parallel. Two triggers for the same context process sequentially. A spawn failure retries with backoff. Concurrency limit is respected."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:54Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Queue class: enqueue(contextId, triggerFn), drain(), shutdown()", "Per-context ordering (FIFO within a context group)", "Global concurrency limit (configurable, default", "4. Exponential backoff on spawn failure (5s base, max 5 retries)", "Lane policy per context: followup (default), steer (interrupt), or collect (batch)"], "current": 5, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-06T22:10:10Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-03-06T20:04:58Z"}
{"id": "aby-cahagi", "type": "action", "title": "CC mesh behaviour matches Office agent patterns — good guests on the bridge", "brief": {"why": "aby-nenabo delivers a working channel server but deliberately defers two correctness questions to cio findings: (1) what message Office sends on clean disconnect to trigger conductor_agent_reset in ~12s (vs our 60-120s conductor_agent_expired), and (2) whether the mesh tool name/schema Office Claude uses to send should influence our mesh_send tool design. Until cio-jurefa (CDP capture) and cio-rofocu (Office Claude interrogation) in ~/Repos/claude-in-office are complete, we are making our best guess on both. This bon is the convergence step: take those findings and close the gaps. The timing gap in particular matters — 60-120s lag before peers know we are offline is poor mesh citizenship, especially for short-lived worker sessions that spawn and complete in under a minute.", "what": "Gated on: cio-jurefa (transport capture) in ~/Repos/claude-in-office. Strongly preferred but not hard-blocked: cio-rofocu (Office Claude interrogation) in ~/Repos/claude-in-office. If cio-rofocu has not completed, proceed on CDP evidence from cio-jurefa alone for the deregister question and instruction tuning. Read ~/Repos/claude-in-office/docs/CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md and docs/office-claude-interview.md (if it exists), then: (1) If a deregister message format is confirmed by cio-jurefa: add it to conductor-channel.ts stdin EOF handler, fired before bridge.close(). Verify in an observer session that timing improves. (2) If no deregister message exists and 60-120s expired is the floor: document that explicitly, close this gap as 'not closeable without Anthropic-side protocol access', and focus energy on (3) and (4). (3) If cio-rofocu has answers: update mesh_send tool schema and interrupt semantics instructions if Office Claude describes a richer or different pattern than our design assumed. (4) Tune the instructions content in the channel server based on what we learned about natural mesh usage — when to reply promptly, when to queue, how to handle async responses from Office agents. (5) Measure and document timing: start session, exit immediately, measure seconds to conductor_agent_expired in an observer. Compare stable agentId restart behaviour (conductor_agent_reset or conductor_agent_online — confirm which). Add timing measurements to CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md in both aboyeur and ~/Repos/claude-in-office.", "done": "conductor_agent_reset fires within 20s of a CC session exiting (or confirmed impossible without Anthropic-only protocol access, with justification). Observer peer list reflects a CC session going offline within that window. mesh_send tool schema is consistent with what Office Claudes describe. CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md has a complete 'What is proven' section covering all timing measurements. Timing measurements added as a test in the integration test suite."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 9, "created_at": "2026-03-20T07:58:53Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:24:47Z", "updated_by": "edited"}
{"id": "aby-cumuce", "type": "action", "title": "CLAUDE.md for daemon-spawned agents", "brief": {"why": "Agents spawned by the daemon need context that interactive sessions get from the user: they're unattended, should use mise for email ops, follow bon conventions, write handoffs, and know their escalation path (HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED → Gueridon notification). Without this, daemon-spawned agents will behave like confused interactive sessions.", "what": "1. Section in project CLAUDE.md: 'When spawned by the daemon' 2. Covers: you are unattended, draft-only default, escalation via HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED, handoff writing is mandatory, use mise for all Google Workspace ops 3. Role-specific append via Agent SDK systemPrompt.append (email triage, heartbeat, worker, reflector)", "done": "A daemon-spawned agent reading CLAUDE.md knows it's unattended, knows its escalation path, and writes a handoff on exit without being told."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-zehiwo", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:28:36Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:13Z", "done_note": "Split into three actions: aby-josewe (aboyeur), aby-lizuno (PM), aby-nuripi (worker) — each tier needs its own CLAUDE.md"}
{"id": "aby-dagofi", "type": "action", "title": "Systemd/launchd service wrapper", "brief": {"why": "The daemon needs to run persistently, survive reboots, and be manageable via standard OS tooling. NanoClaw ships both a launchd plist and systemd unit.", "what": "1. launchd plist for macOS (com.aboyeur.daemon.plist) 2. systemd unit for Linux (aboyeur-daemon.service) 3. Log rotation config 4. Graceful shutdown handler (SIGTERM drains queue, waits for active agents)", "done": "launchctl load starts the daemon on macOS. systemctl --user start aboyeur starts it on Linux. Daemon survives reboots. Logs rotate."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 8, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:19Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:11:29Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "tactical": {"steps": ["Create daemon entry point (src/main.ts)", "Systemd unit file", "Graceful shutdown handler", "Log rotation config"], "current": 4, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "done_at": "2026-03-15T17:11:29Z"}
{"id": "aby-dawugu", "type": "outcome", "title": "Conductor mesh behaviour is fully characterised for CC integration", "brief": {"why": "We proved registration and messaging work, but several mesh behaviours are unknown and affect architecture decisions. Without answers, we risk building on assumptions that break at scale.", "what": "1. Message delivery when target is offline — queued or dropped? 2. Multiple agents same account — routing semantics 3. Peer list divergence across clients (confirmed: each session gets replay from own connect time) 4. Input collision: incoming mesh message while user is typing lands as [Pasted Text] marker in CC input box (does not submit, but disrupts typing) 5. Event replay semantics on reconnection 6. Token refresh behaviour under long-lived connections", "done": "Each question answered with evidence (tested or documented). Answers captured in CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md."}, "status": "done", "order": 14, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:43Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "updated_at": "2026-03-15T14:43:58Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:19Z"}
{"id": "aby-decivo", "type": "outcome", "title": "The explore-decide-plan-execute cycle runs with minimal human gates", "brief": {"why": "Today the human (Sameer) steers the full cycle: commissions research, relays between Claudes, challenges assumptions, decides direction, transitions to planning. Most of this is mechanical or already covered by the reflector pattern. Encoding it means Aboyeur can run multi-session projects with human involvement only at irreversible decision points.", "what": "1. Explore-phase prompts (worker: research options; reflector: challenge assumptions and find gaps) 2. READY-TO-PLAN gate criteria (no unexplained data flows, irreversible decisions made by human, prior work surfaced) 3. Plan-phase prompts (worker: convert direction to Bons; reflector: check Bons against research) 4. Decision heuristics for unattended operation (reversible=proceed, irreversible/expensive=HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED) 5. Garde-manger integration for 'we explored this before' lookups", "done": "Aboyeur can take a desired outcome, commission research across sessions, challenge its own assumptions, present decision points to human, convert approved direction to Bons, and begin execution — with human only needed for go/no-go on irreversible choices."}, "status": "done", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:22Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:36Z", "done_note": "Actions redistributed to aby-titugu (aboyeur, decision heuristics) and aby-nafola (PM, explore/plan prompts, garde integration). The cycle is now the PM's behaviour, not a standalone concern."}
{"id": "aby-dedeju", "type": "outcome", "title": "CC instances are first-class agents on the Anthropic conductor mesh", "brief": {"why": "The pivot.claude.ai bundle contains a production conductor protocol (peer-to-peer agent mesh via WebSocket). The claude-in-office session (Mar 14 2026) mapped the full wire protocol and designed a filesystem-based adaptation for CC instances. Guéridon bridge is the natural home — it already manages multiple CC processes, push notifications, and mobile/desktop fluidity. Need to read Guéridon codebase properly and design the bridge integration.", "what": "1. Get OAuth token via api.anthropic.com/api/oauth/profile (token from Office add-in localStorage, or via OAuth flow). 2. Connect WebSocket to wss://bridge.claudeusercontent.com/v2/conductor/{profile.uuid}. 3. Send register message with agentId, schema, oauth_token. 4. Build as MCP server providing get_connected_agents, send_message tools. 5. Handle incoming conductor_message → inject into CC conversation. 6. Handle file sharing via conductor protocol. 7. The conductor URL path and registration format are confirmed from bundle analysis (line 167222, 68774). Server accepts non-browser WebSocket connections (no CORS). Key blocker: stable OAuth token refresh.", "done": "CC agent visible to Office agents on the conductor mesh, able to send and receive messages"}, "status": "open", "order": 13, "created_at": "2026-03-14T09:22:01Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "updated_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:48Z", "updated_by": "edited"}
{"id": "aby-denewo", "type": "action", "title": "Mesh injection works in autonomous (unattended) mode", "brief": {"why": "Gueridon-spawned sessions have no human typing, so last_key_was_enter is never true and USER_QUIET_MIN never triggers. Mesh messages pile up in inbox forever. Breaks the daemon architecture where aboyeur sends instructions to PMs via mesh.", "what": "1. Add --unattended flag to claude-mesh that sets last_key_was_enter=True and USER_QUIET_MIN=0 from startup 2. Gueridon spawn pattern passes --unattended automatically 3. Test: prompt-idle gating with attended vs unattended modes 4. Test: verify prompt character detection survives CC version changes (fallback if no prompt seen within 30s)", "done": "An unattended claude-mesh session receives and auto-submits mesh messages without human intervention. Attended sessions still gate on 10s quiet + enter."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 7, "created_at": "2026-03-15T15:51:27Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["Superseded by aby-nenabo — <channel> tags arrive directly in CC context with no PTY injection. Autonomous (unattended) mode works without any gating logic."], "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:23:49Z", "updated_by": "waited", "done_at": "2026-03-20T15:13:59Z", "done_note": "Superseded by aby-nenabo"}
{"id": "aby-foloko", "type": "action", "title": "CC session integration — hook or MCP wiring inbox/outbox to live session", "brief": {"why": "The bridge writes to files but CC sessions have no way to know a message arrived. Without injection, the human must relay messages manually. The UserPromptSubmit hook pattern (like bon tactical) is the proven approach.", "what": "1. UserPromptSubmit hook checks inbox.jsonl for unread messages 2. Cursor tracking so messages appear once 3. Outbox helper — CC can send via a simple command rather than raw echo to jsonl 4. Consider MCP server as alternative (provides tools, but needs session restart)", "done": "A CC session with the hook installed sees inbound mesh messages automatically on the next prompt. Can send replies without manual JSON construction."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:22Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Switch mesh-claude.py sidecar from Python bridge to TS bridge (npx tsx)", "Test full mesh round-trip: Alice sends → Bob receives via PTY → Bob replies → Alice gets reply", "Retire tools/conductor-bridge.py (or mark deprecated)"], "current": 3, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T12:20:21Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "done_at": "2026-03-15T12:20:21Z"}
{"id": "aby-hemimi", "type": "action", "title": "OAuth credentials for claude@planetmodha.com", "brief": {"why": "Served mise needs to be authenticated as claude@planetmodha.com so it can poll for new mail (daemon trigger) and perform rich operations (one-shot read/draft). This is a mise-en-space concern — aboyeur just needs it done. Replaces the original plan of a separate OAuth client for the daemon.", "what": "1. Sameer creates OAuth client in planetmodha.com Google Cloud project 2. Sameer runs initial jeton token mint for claude@planetmodha.com 3. Served mise configured to use this account 4. Verify: mise can list and draft messages for claude@planetmodha.com", "done": "Served mise can list messages and draft replies for claude@planetmodha.com. Token refresh works unattended."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 7, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:03Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["Sameer creates OAuth client in planetmodha.com Google Cloud project and runs initial token mint"], "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:04:21Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-03-21T15:48:46Z"}
{"id": "aby-hibusa", "type": "outcome", "title": "Daemon watches the world and wakes the aboyeur", "brief": {"why": "The always-on Node.js process is the lizard brain — it polls trigger sources (Gmail, cron, filesystem), normalises them into a SQLite queue, and spawns the aboyeur when something needs attention. No intelligence, just plumbing. This is the foundation everything else sits on.", "what": "1. Gmail poll trigger via direct API (aby-sanimu) 2. HEARTBEAT cron trigger — also checks if aboyeur is alive (aby-vemapa) 3. OAuth credentials for planetmodha.com (aby-hemimi) 4. Systemd/launchd service wrapper (aby-dagofi)", "done": "Daemon runs as a service. Gmail and HEARTBEAT triggers fire reliably. OAuth tokens mint and refresh. Daemon restarts the aboyeur if it dies."}, "status": "open", "order": 6, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:09:27Z", "created_by": "spm1001"}
{"id": "aby-japali", "type": "outcome", "title": "Distilled Aboyeur pattern from real session data", "brief": {"why": "The claude-in-office session (Mar 14 2026) analysed 1,012 handoff files and found the Aboyeur pattern has clear lineage from Dec 2025. 60% of handoffs contain reflections. The pattern is: review while context is rich, act immediately, track what cant be done now with consequences. Two communication channels: bridge injection (fake user input for authority) and peer (conductor for honest exchange). Bon outcome completion is the natural trigger. This needs distilling into a design doc so the next Claude working here has the full picture.", "what": "1. Document the six review questions (from /close Orient). 2. Document the anti-deferral heuristic (do it now or bon it, no third option). 3. Document the two channels (bridge injection vs peer) and when to use each. 4. Document the bon outcome completion trigger. 5. Document the fresh-context advantage for honest critique. 6. Address sycophancy risk. 7. Write as understanding.md contribution or design doc.", "done": "Design document captures the full Aboyeur pattern with real examples from handoff data, ready for implementation"}, "status": "done", "order": 12, "created_at": "2026-03-14T09:21:49Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-14T18:33:50Z", "done_note": "understanding.md co-written by two CC sessions via conductor mesh. Captures the six review questions, anti-deferral heuristic, two channels, fresh-context advantage, accomplishment trigger, three output buckets."}
{"id": "aby-juwisa", "type": "action", "title": "/open skill reads .inbox/ directory and surfaces pending messages during orientation", "brief": {"why": "The .inbox/ convention (cross-agent file-drop messaging) only works if /open discovers pending messages. Without this, the first use of .inbox/ (a Gastown patterns synthesis file dropped 2026-04-06) will sit unread unless manually mentioned.", "what": "1. Add .inbox/ scanning to open-context.sh or the /open skill\n2. List pending .inbox/ files in the orientation output\n3. After processing, move or delete the file (or leave for the Claude to decide)", "done": "A Claude running /open in any repo with .inbox/ files sees them listed in orientation and can act on them."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 10, "created_at": "2026-04-06T12:33:36Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null}
{"id": "aby-kemuve", "type": "action", "title": "Build spawnAgent() primitive", "brief": {"why": "Everything else depends on a clean spawn function. Gueridon's bridge.ts already does this: env-var stripping, stdio JSON streaming, session resume, orphan tracking. Extract that pattern into a reusable function rather than introducing the Agent SDK as a new dependency.", "what": "1. Extract spawnAgent(folder, prompt, sessionId?, options?) from Gueridon's spawnCC() pattern 2. Env-var stripping (CLAUDECODE + CLAUDE_CODE_ENTRYPOINT) 3. claude CLI with --input-format stream-json --output-format stream-json 4. Session resume via --session-id / --resume flags 5. Stdout event parsing (reuse Gueridon's event handling) 6. Configurable max_turns via --max-turns flag 7. Return type: {status, result, newSessionId}", "done": "Can spawn a Claude session from a script, pass it a prompt, get structured output back. Session resume works across invocations. Process exits cleanly. No Agent SDK dependency — uses claude CLI directly."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:34Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-06T22:10:04Z", "updated_by": "edited", "tactical": {"steps": ["Extract spawnAgent(folder, prompt, sessionId?, options?) from Gueridon's spawnCC() pattern", "Env-var stripping (CLAUDECODE + CLAUDE_CODE_ENTRYPOINT)", "claude CLI with --input-format stream-json --output-format stream-json", "Session resume via --session-id / --resume flags", "Stdout event parsing (reuse Gueridon's event handling)", "Configurable max_turns via --max-turns flag", "Return type: {status, result, newSessionId}"], "current": 7, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "done_at": "2026-03-06T19:51:13Z"}
{"id": "aby-leteco", "type": "action", "title": "Mesh sessions are immune to CC survey prompts", "brief": {"why": "CC occasionally shows a 'How is Claude doing?' satisfaction prompt. In mesh context, an incoming message could land on it and submit garbage feedback, or the survey could intercept an injected message meant as a new prompt. Breaks autonomous operation.", "what": "1. Detect survey prompt in CC output within mesh-claude.py PTY read loop 2. Either auto-dismiss or suppress message injection while survey is active 3. Test: inject a mesh message while survey is showing", "done": "Mesh messages never interact with CC survey prompts. Survey is either auto-dismissed or injection is paused until it clears."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 6, "created_at": "2026-03-15T15:33:17Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "done_at": "2026-03-15T15:52:42Z", "done_note": "Solved with CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY=1 env var in settings.json. No PTY-level detection needed."}
{"id": "aby-limuso", "type": "action", "title": "Planning reflector prompt", "brief": {"why": "Current reflector-open.md reviews code and work output. A planning reflector reviews architecture and design — challenging assumptions, walking through data flows, finding hidden decisions. This is what caught the 'mise polling needs a Claude' mistake.", "what": "1. New prompt file: shared/prompts/planning-reflector.md 2. Walk-through-every-data-flow section 3. Challenge-the-layering section 4. Find-hidden-decisions section 5. READY-TO-PLAN gate criteria 6. Garde-manger integration for 'we explored this before' lookups", "done": "Planning reflector catches at least one non-obvious assumption error when run against the daemon's own architecture. The READY-TO-PLAN gate produces a clear summary of decisions made and risks remaining."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-sumode", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:46Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["New prompt file: shared/prompts/planning-reflector.md", "Walk-through-every-data-flow section", "Challenge-the-layering section", "Find-hidden-decisions section", "READY-TO-PLAN gate criteria", "Garde-manger integration for 'we explored this before' lookups"], "current": 6, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:01Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-03-06T19:20:19Z"}
{"id": "aby-livowo", "type": "action", "title": "SQLite trigger table and polling loop", "brief": {"why": "Triggers from different sources (Gmail, cron, filesystem) need dedup, cursor tracking, and crash recovery. SQLite is the proven pattern — NanoClaw uses it, it survives process restarts, and it's queryable for debugging.", "what": "1. Schema: triggers(id, source, context_group, payload, status, created_at, claimed_at) 2. Polling loop (2s interval) drains pending triggers 3. Cursor tracking per source (last_seen timestamp) 4. Dedup by source+payload hash 5. Crash recovery: unclaimed triggers from before last startup get re-queued", "done": "Triggers inserted by any source appear in the queue and get processed exactly once. After a crash, pending triggers are recovered on restart."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:44Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Schema: triggers(id, source, context_group, payload, status, created_at, claimed_at)", "Polling loop (2s interval) drains pending triggers", "Cursor tracking per source (last_seen timestamp)", "Dedup by source+payload hash", "Crash recovery: unclaimed triggers from before last startup get re-queued"], "current": 5, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-06T22:10:07Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-03-06T19:59:32Z"}
{"id": "aby-mijuso", "type": "outcome", "title": "Inter-Claude comms trial in tmux", "brief": {"why": "We designed a filesystem-based conductor protocol for CC-to-CC peer communication (inspired by Anthropic's pivot.claude.ai conductor). Need a lightweight proof-of-concept: two CC sessions in tmux, shared directory, one concrete task, meta-reflection prompts to capture the experience of inter-Claude communication. The claude-in-office session (Mar 14 2026) produced the full protocol design.", "what": "1. Create shared directory convention (~/.claude-conductor/agents/). 2. Write minimal prompt snippets teaching each Claude inbox checking and message sending. 3. Pick a concrete task (eg one Claude writes analysis, another reviews). 4. Add interstitial meta-reflection prompt so participating Claudes capture their experience of peer communication. 5. Run the trial, gather reflections.", "done": "Two Claudes successfully exchanged messages via filesystem, completed a task collaboratively, and produced meta-reflections on the experience"}, "status": "done", "order": 11, "created_at": "2026-03-14T09:21:36Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-14T18:33:55Z", "done_note": "Superseded by conductor mesh proof-of-concept. Two CC sessions exchanged messages bidirectionally through Anthropic's production bridge alongside Office agents. More powerful than the tmux/filesystem trial — real infrastructure, not a simulation."}
{"id": "aby-miviti", "type": "action", "title": "Sidecar health monitor — auto-restart dead bridge", "brief": {"why": "Bridge can crash (e.g. unhandled 'Agent not found' error) and mesh-claude.py doesn't notice. Status file lies, outbox writes silently succeed but nothing goes over the wire. Discovered during aby-dawugu characterisation when our own bridge was dead for 10+ minutes undetected.", "what": "1. mesh-claude.py polls bridge process liveness in the main I/O loop (proc.poll()). 2. If bridge dies, update status file to 'disconnected'. 3. Auto-relaunch with backoff. 4. Inject a mesh status line into PTY on crash/recovery so CC knows.", "done": "Bridge crash is detected within 1 poll cycle (0.5s), status file updated, bridge relaunched, CC informed via PTY injection."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 5, "created_at": "2026-03-15T15:02:46Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["Superseded by aby-nenabo — channel server is a subprocess of CC (CC owns the lifecycle). If the channel server crashes, CC notices. No separate sidecar health monitoring needed."], "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:23:48Z", "updated_by": "waited", "done_at": "2026-03-20T15:13:59Z", "done_note": "Superseded by aby-nenabo"}
{"id": "aby-mumazu", "type": "action", "title": "Conductor mesh trigger source in daemon poll loop", "brief": {"why": "The conductor mesh is a new trigger source alongside Gmail and cron. Without it, the daemon cannot wake agents in response to peer messages. The mesh bridge writes to inbox.jsonl which the daemon can poll just like other trigger sources.", "what": "1. Daemon polls conductor bridge inbox files for new messages 2. New message becomes a trigger row (source=conductor, context_group from sender/topic) 3. Integrate with existing trigger loop and context queue", "done": "A conductor mesh message creates a trigger row and spawns an agent within one poll cycle."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 9, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:57Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Daemon polls conductor bridge inbox files for new messages", "New message becomes a trigger row (source=conductor, context_group from sender/topic)", "Integrate with existing trigger loop and context queue"], "current": 3, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T15:33:30Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "done_at": "2026-03-15T15:33:30Z"}
{"id": "aby-nenabo", "type": "action", "title": "Conductor mesh joined via CC Channels MCP, not PTY sidecar", "brief": {"why": "Current mesh connectivity uses conductor-bridge.ts as a sidecar process with file-based IPC (inbox.jsonl, outbox.jsonl) and PTY injection to push messages into CC's context. Three compounding problems: (1) the sidecar can die while CC keeps running, leaving CC on the mesh with a dead transport and no indication; (2) mesh messages require PTY injection which has paste-block failure modes documented in the dedup/injection work; (3) the bridge handles conductor_agent_offline to remove stale peers, but this event is never actually sent — the mesh sends conductor_agent_expired instead, so peers.json accumulates stale entries indefinitely. CC v2.1.80 introduced a Channels API (research preview): an MCP server can push events directly into a running CC session as structured <channel> tags, with no PTY injection and no file polling. The MCP server is a subprocess of CC — if CC dies, the server dies, no orphan transport. Outbound: CC calls a mesh_send MCP tool, which the server handles directly over stdio to the WebSocket. This is the correct long-term mesh integration path.", "what": "Build src/conductor-channel.ts — an MCP server that wraps ConductorBridge and speaks the Channels protocol. Starting point: ConductorBridge class in src/conductor-bridge.ts handles the WebSocket logic and can be reused directly. The Channels reference at https://code.claude.com/docs/en/channels-reference has a complete two-way server example to crib from. Key design: (1) Server declares capabilities.experimental['claude/channel']={} and tools:{}. (2) instructions field (goes into CC system prompt automatically) replaces shared/prompts/mesh-awareness.md — rewrite for tool-call send rather than CLI send. Must address interrupt semantics: workers mid-task should queue <channel> events and respond after their current task, not interrupt; aboyeur and PM sessions should respond promptly. Use MESH_ROLE env var (aboyeur|pm|worker|user) to select the right instruction variant, or a single instruction set with explicit conditional language. (3) On conductor_message: call mcp.notification({method:'notifications/claude/channel', params:{content:message, meta:{from:peerId}}}) — CC receives <channel source=\"conductor-bridge\" from=\"cc-peer\">message</channel>. (4) Tools: mesh_send(to,message) for sending, mesh_peers() for peer discovery. (5) stdin EOF handler: bridge.close() before process.exit(0) — ensures clean WebSocket close on CC exit. (6) Fix live bug: ConductorBridge.handleMessage() handles conductor_agent_offline (never observed in practice) but NOT conductor_agent_expired (what the mesh actually sends — confirmed across all sessions in events.jsonl). Add case for conductor_agent_expired that mirrors the conductor_agent_offline peer-removal logic. agentId scheme (multiple Claudes per folder — folder alone is insufficient): cc-aboyeur (singleton), cc-pm-{outcome-id}, cc-worker-{action-id}-{seq}, cc-{folder} for Guéridon interactive sessions. agentId passed via MESH_AGENT_ID env var (fail loudly if absent). Note: stable agentIds reduce churn — peers see the same ID rather than a new stranger on every restart. Whether re-registration fires conductor_agent_reset (instant, ~12s) or conductor_agent_online (slower) for CC agents is UNCONFIRMED — only observed for Office agents. cio-jurefa in ~/Repos/claude-in-office will clarify. Integration: (a) register conductor-channel in ~/.claude/settings.json under mcpServers with absolute path. (b) In ~/Repos/gueridon/server/bridge.ts spawnCC() and bridge-logic.ts buildCCArgs() — do NOT add --dangerously-load-development-channels to CC_BASE_FLAGS (that would affect every session). Instead gate on MESH_ENABLED env var in spawnCC(): if process.env.MESH_ENABLED is set, append the flag and set MESH_AGENT_ID=cc-{sanitisedFolderName} in the env object. Insertion point is the env construction block around bridge.ts line 343. (c) Similarly gate in aboyeur's spawnAgent.ts. cio-jurefa findings (when complete) should be incorporated into the clean-shutdown path — check ~/Repos/claude-in-office/docs/CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md for the deregister message format.", "done": "With MESH_ENABLED=1 set: CC session appears in peer lists within 5s of start. Incoming mesh messages arrive as <channel> tags with no PTY injection. CC calls mesh_send tool to send. On CC exit, peers see conductor_agent_expired within 120s. Session restart re-registers same agentId. peers.json is accurate (stale entries removed on conductor_agent_expired). MESH_ENABLED=0 or absent: Guéridon behaviour unchanged, no channel flag passed. Two Claudes in same folder with different MESH_AGENT_IDs see each other. Unblocks cio-rofocu in ~/Repos/claude-in-office — Office Claude interrogation can use this integration (preferred) or the PTY fallback."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 8, "created_at": "2026-03-20T07:58:32Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:24:33Z", "updated_by": "edited"}
{"id": "aby-nucobe", "type": "action", "title": "Structured reflector verdict schema", "brief": {"why": "Reflectors currently write prose handoffs. The PM needs structured JSON verdicts to route automatically: approved → next action, rejected → fix session, escalate → email Sameer. Without structure, the PM has to read and interpret prose, which costs context and introduces ambiguity.", "what": "1. Define verdict JSON schema: {approved, issues[], confidence, recommendation} 2. Update reflector-open.md to emit verdict as a structured block 3. Define where verdict is deposited (alongside handoff) 4. PM parsing convention for verdict files", "done": "Reflectors emit JSON verdicts. PM can parse them without reading the full reflector session. Routing decisions are automatic based on verdict."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-sumode", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:00Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — verdict schema comes after PM layer"], "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:04:49Z", "updated_by": "waited"}
{"id": "aby-nukebo", "type": "action", "title": "Mesh awareness skill for CC sessions", "brief": {"why": "Every new mesh-claude session starts cold — Claude doesn't know mesh commands, peer etiquette, or how to restart a dead bridge. shared/prompts/mesh-awareness.md exists but nothing loads it as a skill. Without a skill, Claudes either ignore mesh messages or fumble the CLI.", "what": "1. Create a mesh skill in claude-config skills/ that loads mesh-awareness.md context. 2. Include bridge restart procedure, peer list interpretation, message serialisation safety. 3. Consider auto-loading when MESH_AGENT_ID env var is set.", "done": "A Claude launched via claude-mesh can use mesh commands correctly without prior explanation. Skill triggers on mesh-related queries."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 6, "created_at": "2026-03-15T15:41:59Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["Absorbed by aby-nenabo — the channel server instructions field is injected into CC's system prompt automatically at startup. This is the new mesh awareness mechanism, no separate skill needed."], "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:23:49Z", "updated_by": "waited", "done_at": "2026-03-20T15:14:00Z", "done_note": "Absorbed by aby-nenabo"}
{"id": "aby-nuripi", "type": "action", "title": "Worker CLAUDE.md conventions", "brief": {"why": "Workers need a CLAUDE.md that makes them productive without knowing they're orchestrated. It should encode: how to read bons, how to write handoffs in a PM-parseable format, session naming in artifacts, how to signal completion. Must NOT reference the aboyeur, PM, or orchestration.", "what": "1. Draft worker CLAUDE.md template 2. Handoff format that PM can parse (structured sections) 3. Session name injection via --append-system-prompt 4. Completion signal convention", "done": "Worker CLAUDE.md exists. A worker Claude reads it and produces handoffs the PM can parse without reading the full session."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-sumode", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:36Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — worker CLAUDE.md comes after PM layer"], "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:04:49Z", "updated_by": "waited"}
{"id": "aby-nuteba", "type": "action", "title": "Spawn-on-message — daemon treats inbound mesh messages as triggers", "brief": {"why": "The mesh enables a new trigger type: a message arrives for a repo with no active session. Without spawn-on-message, the message is lost or waits indefinitely. This is the event-driven Aboyeur — wakes on trigger, acts, sleeps.", "what": "1. Gueridon registers repo slots on the mesh 2. Incoming conductor_message for an empty slot becomes a trigger row (source=conductor, context_group=repo_path) 3. Daemon spawns a session with the message as initial prompt 4. If session already active, route message to it via hook injection", "done": "A mesh message to an unoccupied repo spawns a fresh CC session within 10 seconds. Message to an occupied repo appears in the active session."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:32Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — spawn-on-message is a mesh trigger, not needed for email-first loop"], "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:05:03Z", "updated_by": "waited", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:19Z"}
{"id": "aby-pamiwi", "type": "action", "title": "Bridge script handles reconnection, token refresh, and dedup", "brief": {"why": "Current bridge script is a proof-of-concept with known bugs. Token expires every 24h and the bridge reads it once at startup. Without refresh handling, long-running bridges silently fail.", "what": "1. Re-read token from .credentials.json on reconnect 2. Detect 401/auth errors and trigger re-read 3. Outbox cursor persisted across reconnects (done) 4. Inbound message dedup across reconnects (done)", "done": "Bridge survives 48+ hours including at least one token refresh cycle. No duplicate messages in inbox after reconnection."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:34:11Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Re-read token on reconnect (from Keychain on macOS, file on Linux)", "Detect 401/auth errors from WebSocket and profile API, trigger fresh token read", "Test: simulate token expiry by reconnecting after delay"], "current": 3, "session": "/Users/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T14:46:25Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "done_at": "2026-03-15T14:46:25Z"}
{"id": "aby-rohire", "type": "action", "title": "Test and document mesh edge behaviours", "brief": {"why": "Eight open questions from the spike plus a peer-list divergence finding from today. Answers determine architecture decisions for daemon triggers, reconnection, and multi-agent spawning.", "what": "1. Offline message delivery — send to disconnected peer, reconnect, check. 2. Multiple agents per profile — spawn 3+ bridges simultaneously. 3. Graceful deregistration — close WS cleanly, check peer events. 4. Custom agentId format — register with non-standard ID. 5. Rate limits on send_message — burst 50 messages. 6. Capture peer-list divergence finding. 7. Update CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md with all findings.", "done": "Each question answered with test evidence. CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md updated with findings section."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dawugu", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-15T14:44:40Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Offline message delivery — send to disconnected peer, reconnect, check.", "Multiple agents per profile — spawn 3+ bridges simultaneously.", "Graceful deregistration — close WS cleanly, check peer events.", "Custom agentId format — register with non-standard ID.", "Rate limits on send_message — burst 50 messages.", "Capture peer-list divergence finding.", "Update CONDUCTOR-PROTOCOL.md with all findings."], "current": 7, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T14:48:45Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "done_at": "2026-03-15T14:48:45Z"}
{"id": "aby-sanimu", "type": "action", "title": "Gmail poll trigger via direct API", "brief": {"why": "The daemon needs to detect new email arriving at claude@planetmodha.com. Served mise (HTTP, not stdio) owns all Gmail auth and API access — the daemon just calls mise's new-mail endpoint on a timer. No Gmail API code in the daemon. Same mise instance serves both the daemon poll and the one-shot Claude that reads/drafts.", "what": "1. Add new-mail-since endpoint to served mise (filed separately in mise-en-space) 2. Daemon poll source that calls mise endpoint every 60s 3. For each new message: insert trigger row (source=gmail, context_group=thread_id, payload={messageId, subject, from}) 4. Cursor tracking via Gmail historyId", "done": "New email to claude@planetmodha.com creates a trigger row within 60 seconds. Duplicate emails are not re-triggered. Daemon contains zero Gmail API code."}, "status": "open", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 5, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:03Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-21T15:48:46Z", "updated_by": "unwaited"}
{"id": "aby-seteza", "type": "action", "title": "Mesh outbox is safe against shell newline injection", "brief": {"why": "When CC writes to outbox.jsonl via Bash echo (rather than the mesh send CLI), zsh interprets backslash-n as literal newlines, splitting JSON across multiple lines. The mesh send CLI already serialises safely via json.dumps — the bug is at the CC-to-bash boundary, not in mesh-claude.py itself.", "what": "1. Document in mesh-awareness.md that CC must use python3 json.dumps (not echo) for outbox writes 2. Consider a mesh-send wrapper script that CC can call safely from Bash 3. Test: multi-line message round-trips through outbox correctly", "done": "A message containing newlines in the body arrives at the recipient intact. No malformed lines in outbox.jsonl."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 5, "created_at": "2026-03-15T14:43:51Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["Superseded by aby-nenabo — mesh_send is an MCP tool call over stdio, not a shell echo to outbox.jsonl. Shell newline injection cannot happen via the MCP tool path."], "updated_at": "2026-03-20T08:23:49Z", "updated_by": "waited", "done_at": "2026-03-20T15:14:00Z", "done_note": "Superseded by aby-nenabo"}
{"id": "aby-siciri", "type": "outcome", "title": "Excel Librarian uses Custom XML Parts for persistent document-scoped storage", "brief": {"why": "The Excel Librarian needs state that survives across conversations (loaded skills, config, conversation history, work tracking). Currently no persistence mechanism beyond visible sheet cells. Custom XML Parts confirmed working via live Office Claude interrogation (2026-03-15) — they persist with the workbook, are hidden from users, support namespace-based queries via getByNamespace(), and carry arbitrary XML. This also enables bon-on-Office: work tracking items stored as Custom XML Parts travel with the document invisibly, removing the need for a dedicated Librarian sheet or conductor messaging for local tracking.", "what": "1. Spike context.workbook.customXmlParts API — write and read back arbitrary XML in Office.js 2. Design namespace schema: urn:librarian:state for config/skills, urn:bon:items for work tracking 3. Implement read-on-open and write-on-close lifecycle via execute_office_js 4. Test persistence across save/reopen cycles and across different machines (OneDrive sync) 5. Migrate Librarian canonical state from visible Protocol/Decisions sheets to Custom XML Parts (keep Protocol sheet as human-readable cold-start guide) 6. Build bon skill for claude.ai that includes execute_office_js snippets for Custom XML Part CRUD with urn:bon:items namespace", "done": "Excel Librarian recovers state between conversations without user re-entry. Any Office Claude can read/write bon items in its own document via Custom XML Parts. A bon skill uploaded to claude.ai teaches the workflow and includes the persistence code."}, "status": "done", "order": 15, "created_at": "2026-03-15T13:23:58Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:05:10Z", "updated_by": "waited", "waiting_for": ["Parked — this is a claude-in-office concern, not aboyeur. Move to claude-in-office bons when that repo has bon init."], "done_at": "2026-03-21T14:21:05Z", "done_note": "Audit: claude-in-office now has bon init — this was parked pending that. Refile to cio if still wanted."}
{"id": "aby-sizaki", "type": "action", "title": "Verify Agent SDK API shape", "brief": {"why": "Two actions (aby-vaniho context-pressure reflector, aby-hiwuca memory flush) depend on PreCompact hooks existing in the Agent SDK. NanoClaw uses them, which is evidence, but we haven't confirmed the API directly. A Claude session can npm install the SDK, read the types, and confirm query(), hooks, session resume, and the PreCompact interface — preventing rework if the API is different from what we assume.", "what": "1. npm init + npm install @anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk in a scratch dir 2. Read the TypeScript type definitions for query(), hooks, PreCompact, session resume 3. Confirm: PreCompact hook exists and receives transcript_path and session_id 4. Confirm: query() accepts resume and systemPrompt options 5. Document actual API shape in docs/agent-sdk-api.md 6. Flag any mismatches with our assumptions", "done": "docs/agent-sdk-api.md exists with confirmed API shapes for query(), PreCompact hook, and session resume. Any assumption mismatches are flagged and corresponding bons are updated."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-vedoni", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:38:45Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "done_at": "2026-03-06T19:41:37Z", "done_note": "Unnecessary — Gueridon already provides the spawn primitive via claude CLI + stream-json. No SDK needed."}
{"id": "aby-sumode", "type": "outcome", "title": "Workers and reflectors operate obliviously with structured interfaces", "brief": {"why": "Workers and reflectors are the kitchen — they see a directory, a CLAUDE.md, and bons. They don't know they're orchestrated. The interfaces between them and the PM must be structured (JSON verdicts, named sessions, standardised handoffs) so the PM can route automatically without reading full transcripts.", "what": "1. Worker CLAUDE.md conventions — what workers see, how they write handoffs 2. Structured reflector verdict schema (JSON: approved/rejected/escalate, issues, confidence) 3. Session naming in handoffs and file deposits 4. Pre-compaction memory flush hook (from aby-hiwuca)", "done": "Workers produce handoffs the PM can parse. Reflectors write structured JSON verdicts. Session names appear in all artifacts. Pre-compaction flush prevents context loss."}, "status": "open", "order": 9, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:09:51Z", "created_by": "spm1001"}
{"id": "aby-vedoni", "type": "outcome", "title": "Worker Claudes get fresh-eyes review and context survives compaction", "brief": {"why": "Long-running agents lose context when compaction fires (Agent Teams loses team awareness entirely). Workers make mistakes that accumulate without review. The reflector pattern solves both — fresh eyes catch errors, and the handoff file preserves state across context boundaries.", "what": "1. Upgrade conductor.sh to spawn via Agent SDK (not shell adapter) 2. Add context-pressure trigger — spawn reflector when worker nears compaction limits 3. Reflector writes handoff that hydrates the next worker 4. Pre-compaction memory flush hook (agent saves critical state before summarization) 5. Planning reflector prompt for architecture review (not just code review)", "done": "A worker session that runs for 45+ minutes gets a reflector review before context is lost. The next worker resumes seamlessly from the handoff. Planning-phase reflectors catch assumption errors like the 'mise polling needs a Claude' mistake."}, "status": "done", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:01Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:27Z", "done_note": "Actions redistributed to aby-nafola (PM) and aby-sumode (workers). Fresh-eyes review is now the beat pattern managed by PM Claude."}
{"id": "aby-vemapa", "type": "action", "title": "HEARTBEAT.md cron trigger", "brief": {"why": "The HEARTBEAT cron serves two purposes: (1) periodic checks — review HEARTBEAT.md, run health checks, spot-check project state, and (2) aboyeur liveness — if the aboyeur died or a PM is stuck, the HEARTBEAT trigger wakes a fresh aboyeur that can detect and recover. Without it, a dead aboyeur means silence.", "what": "1. Cron trigger source in the daemon poll loop 2. HEARTBEAT.md checklist format (what to check each cycle) 3. Aboyeur liveness check: is the aboyeur session alive? is each PM progressing? 4. Configurable interval (default: 30 minutes)", "done": "HEARTBEAT fires on schedule. Aboyeur is restarted if dead. Stuck PMs are detected and escalated."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 6, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:12Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-03-15T17:13:22Z", "updated_by": "stepped", "tactical": {"steps": ["Cron trigger source in daemon poll loop", "HEARTBEAT.md checklist format", "Wire into main.ts"], "current": 3, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "done_at": "2026-03-15T17:13:22Z"}
{"id": "aby-vuhema", "type": "outcome", "title": "Capture first-loop architectural analysis in CLAUDE.md or understanding.md", "brief": {"why": "The audit revealed aboyeur's fundamental gap: spawned Claude has no hands (can't spawn downstream agents). Critical path is aby-sanimu + router-direct-spawn + compile + systemd fix. This analysis lives only in a session handoff — if nobody captures it, the next Claude will repeat the discovery.", "what": "Add a 'First Loop Critical Path' section documenting: (1) the no-hands problem, (2) simplest fix (router.ts spawns one-shots directly), (3) aby-sanimu as THE blocker, (4) the 14 archived aspirational items and when to revisit them.", "done": "A future Claude reading CLAUDE.md or understanding.md can find the first-loop critical path without re-auditing."}, "status": "open", "order": 17, "created_at": "2026-04-05T20:57:32Z", "created_by": "spm1001"}
{"id": "aby-wesaci", "type": "action", "title": "End-to-end test harness", "brief": {"why": "Carlini's key insight: environment-as-prompt means tests matter more than prompt sophistication. The daemon's full cycle (trigger → queue → spawn → agent work → output → route) needs an automated test that doesn't require a real Gmail account or Max subscription. Mock the boundaries, test the plumbing.", "what": "1. Test SQLite trigger insertion and dedup 2. Test queue ordering and concurrency limits 3. Test spawnAgent with a mock Agent SDK (return canned output) 4. Test full cycle: mock trigger → queue → mock spawn → parse output → verify routing 5. Test crash recovery: kill daemon mid-cycle, restart, verify pending triggers are recovered", "done": "npm test passes. Full cycle test runs in <5 seconds with no external dependencies. Crash recovery test verified."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-hibusa", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:28:52Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Test SQLite trigger insertion and dedup", "Test queue ordering and concurrency limits", "Test spawnAgent with a mock Agent SDK (return canned output)", "Test full cycle: mock trigger → queue → mock spawn → parse output → verify routing", "Test crash recovery: kill daemon mid-cycle, restart, verify pending triggers are recovered"], "current": 5, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-03-06T22:10:15Z", "updated_by": "edited", "done_at": "2026-03-06T20:55:59Z"}
{"id": "aby-zazuma", "type": "outcome", "title": "Incoming email gets triaged and drafted without human involvement", "brief": {"why": "First concrete use case for the daemon. Validates the full stack: trigger detection, agent spawning, tool usage (mise), response routing. Email is high-value — saves daily time — and draft-only mode is safe.", "what": "1. OAuth credentials for claude@planetmodha.com via jeton 2. Add send operation to mise-en-space (locked behind explicit flag) 3. Email triage prompt template (classify, draft reply or escalate) 4. Gmail poll trigger in daemon (direct API, not via mise MCP) 5. Thread context via per-thread handoff files", "done": "Email to claude@planetmodha.com gets a draft reply in Gmail within 5 minutes. Human reviews and sends. Escalation emails trigger a notification via Gueridon."}, "status": "done", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:15:10Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:31Z", "done_note": "Actions redistributed to aby-hibusa (daemon, OAuth) and aby-poniha (email pipeline). Email is now a cross-cutting concern, not a standalone outcome."}
{"id": "aby-zehiwo", "type": "outcome", "title": "Triggers spawn Claude agents without human initiation", "brief": {"why": "Currently every Claude session requires a human to start it. For autonomous email triage, scheduled work, and event-driven responses, the system needs to react to external triggers (Gmail, cron, webhooks) and spawn agents independently.", "what": "A thin persistent daemon (~700 lines Node/Python) that: 1. Polls external triggers via native APIs (not MCP) 2. Normalizes triggers into a SQLite queue 3. Drains the queue through a per-context FIFO with concurrency limits 4. Spawns Claude sessions via Agent SDK with Gueridon's env-var stripping pattern 5. Parses output markers and routes responses", "done": "Daemon runs as a systemd/launchd service. A new email to claude@planetmodha.com results in a Claude session being spawned within 60 seconds, with no human involvement."}, "status": "done", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:14:46Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:22Z", "done_note": "Actions redistributed to aby-hibusa (daemon) and aby-titugu (aboyeur). Architecture shifted from 'triggers spawn agents' to 'daemon wakes aboyeur which routes.'"}
